.TH "ANIMATIONTIMELINE.DURATION" "3JS" "September 22, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
AnimationTimeline.duration \- AnimationTimeline: duration property
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]duration\f[B]\f[R] read\-only property of the Web
Animations API\(cqs \f[CR]AnimationTimeline\f[R] interface returns the
maximum value for this timeline or \f[CR]null\f[R].
.PP
Note that the derived interfaces \f[CR]ViewTimeline\f[R] and
\f[CR]ScrollTimeline\f[R] always return a duration of 100%, while
\f[CR]DocumentTimeline\f[R] has no duration, and returns
\f[CR]null\f[R].
.SH VALUE
A number representing the timeline\(cqs duration (the maximum value for
this timeline) or \f[CR]null\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS View timeline duration
The \f[CR]ViewTimeline\f[R] always returns a duration of 100% as a
\f[CR]CSSUnitValue\f[R].
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] subject = document.querySelector(\(dq.subject\(dq);
\f[B]const\f[R] timeline = \f[B]new\f[R] ViewTimeline({
  subject,
  axis: \(dqblock\(dq,
});

timeline.duration; \f[I]// CSSUnitValue { value: 100, unit: \(dqpercent\(dq }\f[R]
.EE
.SS Scroll timeline duration
The \f[CR]ScrollTimeline\f[R] always returns a duration of 100% as a
\f[CR]CSSUnitValue\f[R].
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] timeline = \f[B]new\f[R] ScrollTimeline({
  source: document.documentElement,
  axis: \(dqblock\(dq,
});

timeline.duration; \f[I]// CSSUnitValue { value: 100, unit: \(dqpercent\(dq }\f[R]
.EE
.SS Document timeline duration
The \f[CR]DocumentTimeline\f[R] has no duration.
.IP
.EX
document.timeline.duration; \f[I]// null\f[R]
.EE
